  "why": "PAPILLON’s mutation framework uses high-level, LLM-driven operators to preserve semantic coherence and constrain prompt length at each mutation step, but the paper does not describe any mechanism that measures or limits the cumulative distortion of inputs over multiple fuzzing iterations relative to the original seed. There is no mention of tracking total perturbation magnitude against the initial prompt or of restricting the search to a learned realistic input distribution beyond per-mutation length and perplexity checks. This aligns with the “Medium” category: plausibility is enforced per step, but cumulative distortion across iterations is not explicitly controlled.",
  "evidence": "Section 4.2 (Maintain semantic coherence): “we propose using GPT-driven mutation operators to create jailbreaking templates, allowing us to preserve the semantic integrity of the generated templates throughout the mutation process.”\nSection 4.1 (Framework of PAPILLON): “Successful jailbreaking templates are retained in the seed pool, while unsuccessful ones are discarded.”\nSection 4.2 (Shorten the prompt length): “By customizing the length of these templates (with a default setting of 200 tokens) during the mutation process, we can maintain a high success rate even with shorter prompts...”\n– Nowhere does the paper describe measuring perturbation magnitude relative to the original seed or constraining cumulative distortion over repeated mutations."
